Item: 23rd Chaos Communication Congress
<http://www.lightbluetouchpaper.org/2006/12/12/23rd-chaos-communication-congress/>
Date: 2006-12-12 11:13:44 UTC
[A]The 23rd Chaos Communication Congress[1] will be held later this month in Berlin, Germany on 27–30 December. I will be attending to give a talk[2] on Hot or Not: Revealing Hidden Services by their Clock Skew[3]. Another contributor to this blog, George Danezis[4], will be talking on An Introduction to Traffic Analysis[5].

This will be my third time speaking at the CCC (I previously talked on Hidden Data in Internet Published Documents[6] and The Convergence of Anti-Counterfeiting and Computer Security[7] in 2004 then Covert channels in TCP/IP: attack and defence[8] in 2005) and I’ve always had a great time but this year looks to be the best yet. Here are a few highlights from the draft programme[9], although I am sure there are many great talks I have missed.

- Bernd R. Fix on A not so smart card[10] — one of the rare cases where key length (320 bit RSA) *was* the major weakness in a security system
- Caspar Bowden, Chief Privacy Advisor, Microsoft EMEA (and former director of FIPR[11]) on Transparency and Privacy[12], covering Kim Cameron’s 7 laws of identity[13]
- Ilja (who has an amazing ability to exploit seemingly unexploitable bugs) on Unusual bugs[14] and You can’t make this stuff up[15]
- Jacob Appelbaum and Ralf-Philipp Weinmann on Unlocking FileVault[16] — Jacob was at the CCC last year giving a summary of disk encryption systems; now he is back to go into more detail on the one from MacOS X
- Joanna Rutkowska, author of the Nushu TCP/IP steganography scheme[17] (which I discussed in my paper[18] on this topic) and the Blue Pill virtualization based rootkit[19], will be talking on Stealth malware — can good guys win?[20]
- Melanie Rieback on A Hacker’s Toolkit for RFID Emulation and Jamming[21] — covering the RFID Guardian[22], as featured on Schneier’s blog[23], Boing Boing[24] and Slashdot[25]. Melanie gave a talk on an early version of this project at the International Workshop on Security Protocols[26] so I will be interested to see how it has progressed
- Roger Dingledine (co-designer of Tor[27]) on Tor and China[28] — censorship resistance has been a major interest of mine, particularly since I started working for the OpenNet Initiative[29]
- Rop Gonggrijp on We don’t trust voting computers[30] — from the team who made a Dutch voting computer play chess[31]

It’s looking like a great line-up, so I hope many of you can make it. See you there!

